Fukushima and the collapse of derivative products
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the earthquakes, tsunami, and nuclear disaster in Japan to the role of derivative products in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates large profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the manner of preventing their reappearance begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with typically harmless design flaws, caused the cessation of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
With regard to financial markets, an unanticipated collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in the derivatives and repos markets, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the underlying risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, excessive lending for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck have made it so that the systems could not contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers – all with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos – went bankrupt, causing a freeze of credit on the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
One cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives that shook the global economy.
At Fukushima, the teams of workers bravely attempt to stop the radiation leaks.
By contrast, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating similar derivatives and financial structures, above the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial instruments to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuation but does not want the risk on the yen, while for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second promises to provide yens.
If a currency loses value relative to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Repos are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the term "repo," which is an abbreviation for the English verb "repurchase" – or to repurchase, note).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term repos represents a large portion of the balance sheets of the largest financial institutions, which means that even minor financial tremors can affect them significantly.
Some institutions may then find themselves unable to secure repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as Bear Stearns did.
Individually, derivative transactions or repos are hardly blamable.
Each separately legitimately transfers the risk to those who are better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are systemically vital, they can cause the financial system to collapse due to its design flaws.
Today, nearly 70% of the liabilities of major U.S. financial institutions consist of very short-term loans, such as overnight repos.
In the United States, the main design flaws lie in the bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts or repos with financially weakened institutions can seize the company's assets before—and at the expense of—its regular creditors. In doing so, they can decide the company's fate, whereas, with a little more time, the company in question could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repos find themselves at the front of the repayment line in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely checking the solvability of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be repaid, regardless.
Of course, someone must be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions granted to derivative and repo holders place these actors at the front line in the event of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect that the others therefore have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in line is often the U.S. government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to be allowed to fail, note). Yet, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The U.S. Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw during the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer through the Dodd Frank Act.
But he did not seize it.
If derivative, repo, and credit-default swap (credit event derivatives, note) investors did not enjoy favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and above all, they would insist more often that their counterparties be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalizations when it was essentially American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money they were risking.
The public perceives differently the risks of the Fukushima type and the risks linked to derivatives.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
But the derivative and repo markets present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to discuss and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract the public's attention and contempt, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own fate with the legislative body.
Regarding the risks of the Fukushima type, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain the risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
It is now considered possible to design nuclear power plants capable of maintaining cold fuel rods even in the event of a complete power outage.
However, few significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damage that the priority of derivative and repo holders in the event of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, requiring that end users (such as oil companies using derivatives to hedge against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak incentives for market discipline among major financial institutions.
It seems as if we are responding to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully place on derivative and repo investors the risk associated with their decisions when they engage in transactions with financially systemic institutions.
Instead, we have survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same defective design.
